HOWTO {[2J[0;1m!JIf you've never played an adventure game before, the
"obsolete" way of communicating with words may seem unusual -- but think of
the sheer power of language, the power of your mouse finger, and you'll see
that communicating through natural language is much more powerful and
intuitive than pointing and clicking.!)

!JAt any rate, a little help is always helpful. For starters: if a game
crashes for any reason, or you want to quit in a hurry, press
[33mCtrl-C[37m. We'll try our best to interpret the usual exit command
([33mX[37m), but this isn't always possible (for instance with the Z-Machine
is displaying a menu).!)

!JIf you're in a menu without obvious navigation instructions, turn on your
[33mNum Lock[37m and use the arrow keys on your numeric keypad, or the
[33m8[37m, [33m2[37m, [33m6[37m and [33m4[37m keys (respectively up,
down, right, left).!)

!JIf you're stuck with a game, try the [33mHELP[37m command. Some games
include hints and tips or even their own walkthroughs somewhere in their menu
systems. Enter [33mSAVE[37m to save a game (the saved game will be offered
for download), or [33mRESTORE[37m to load a previously saved game (you'll be
asked to upload the game file).!)

!JUse simple English sentences to communicate. In most cases, two words are
enough (verb-object). No articles are necessary, but most games will
understand them if you feel like typing syntantically correct English. If a
game needs more details, it'll say so.!)

!JIssue the [33mLOOK[37m command to look around. You can move around with
the usual shorthands [33mN[37m, [33mS[37m, [33mE[37m and [33mW[37m
(North, South, East, West respectively).!)

!JFinally, outside of menus, BBS global commands work too. [32mCAUTION[37m:
you can use the [33m/GO[37m command to leave a game in a hurry, but in doing
so you [32mforfeit[37m your game. Consider saving the game first.!)

